00:12.429 --> 00:14.263
(CAR ENGINES RUNNING)

00:47.715 --> 00:49.340
(CROWD CHEERING)

03:48.645 --> 03:50.062
(TIRES SCREECHING)

03:52.232 --> 03:53.608
(CRASHING)

06:18.795 --> 06:20.087
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

06:20.172 --> 06:21.714
(TIRES SCREECHING)

06:45.280 --> 06:46.906
(BOTH IMITATING
CAR ENGINE)

06:52.454 --> 06:53.954
Hang on,
we're coming to a bend.

06:54.039 --> 06:55.289
You're going too fast!

06:55.373 --> 06:56.791
No, I'm not. Hang on!

06:57.042 --> 06:59.043
What's this heap of
old iron doing here?

06:59.127 --> 07:00.169
Old iron?

07:00.253 --> 07:01.462
I'll give you
10 bob for it.

07:01.546 --> 07:02.755
Don't be daft.

07:02.839 --> 07:04.799
This was once
a great car.

07:04.883 --> 07:07.134
Won the Grand Prix
three years running.

07:07.219 --> 07:09.720
(LAUGHS)
So it's a car, is it?

07:09.930 --> 07:11.305
Certainly
it's a car.

07:11.389 --> 07:13.265
It's a racing car.
And we're winning.

07:13.350 --> 07:14.975
And you're
in the way.

07:15.060 --> 07:17.603
And you're in the way
for a right belt around
the ear, young man,

07:17.687 --> 07:19.605
if I have any
more of your lip.

07:19.689 --> 07:22.900
All right.
I'll give you
15 bob for it.

07:22.984 --> 07:25.361
Make it 30 bob,
and she's yours.

07:25.445 --> 07:28.030
Mr. Coggins,
you're not going to
sell her, are you?

07:28.115 --> 07:29.365
Of course he's
gonna sell her.

07:29.449 --> 07:30.491
What do you think
he's running here,

07:30.575 --> 07:32.451
a children's playground
or something?

07:32.536 --> 07:35.579
All right, 30 bob.
I'll pick her up Wednesday.

07:35.664 --> 07:38.833
But, Mr. Coggins,
you promised we
could play in her.

07:38.917 --> 07:42.628
Well, I'm sorry, my dears,
but she ain't any use to me.

07:42.712 --> 07:43.838
Times are hard.

07:43.922 --> 07:45.548
But you can't
take her away.

07:45.632 --> 07:48.425
She's not just
any old car.
She's ours.

07:48.510 --> 07:51.220
Not anymore, she ain't.
I'll see you tomorrow, Bill.

07:51.304 --> 07:52.304
Giddy-up!

07:52.389 --> 07:54.140
What're you going
to do with her?

07:54.224 --> 07:56.142
I'll tell you what
we're gonna do with her,

07:56.226 --> 07:57.810
we're gonna put her
in the clapper

07:57.894 --> 08:01.147
and we're gonna crunch her up
till she's one
solid piece of metal.

08:01.231 --> 08:03.315
Then we're gonna put her
in a fiery furnace,

08:03.400 --> 08:06.277
and we're gonna melt her down
till she's liquid iron.

08:06.361 --> 08:08.863
That's what we're
gonna do with her.

08:10.073 --> 08:12.700
Now look what you've done.
You've frightened her.

08:12.784 --> 08:13.784
She shivered.

08:13.869 --> 08:15.578
See? She's a very
special car.

08:15.662 --> 08:19.123
If you put her in
the fiery furnace,
you'll be guilty of murder.

08:19.207 --> 08:21.041
Yeah, and if you
don't get out of it,

08:21.126 --> 08:22.585
I'll be guilty of
two more murders.

08:22.669 --> 08:25.713
Now go on, out of it.
Giddy-up! Giddy-up!

08:27.007 --> 08:30.009
Please, Mr. Coggins,
you can't sell
our lovely car

08:30.093 --> 08:31.677
to that nasty man.

08:31.761 --> 08:35.847
Well, I'm sorry, children,
but I'm afraid
I already have.

08:36.433 --> 08:39.309
I know!
Daddy will buy it for us.
Won't he, Jemima?

08:39.394 --> 08:40.519
Of course he will.

08:40.604 --> 08:43.272
Mr. Coggins, promise you
won't let her go
until we come back.

08:43.356 --> 08:44.523
(LAUGHING)

08:44.608 --> 08:48.027
Well, 30 shillings, mind.
Not a penny less.

08:48.111 --> 08:49.153
Please promise.

08:49.237 --> 08:50.279
Please.

08:50.363 --> 08:52.489
All right, I promise.

08:52.574 --> 08:54.158
Come on, Jemima.

08:58.121 --> 08:59.288
(GASPS)

09:00.123 --> 09:01.457
(TIRES SCREECHING)

09:03.460 --> 09:06.045
Well, that's
a clever thing to do!

09:06.254 --> 09:07.630
We're very sorry, miss.

09:07.714 --> 09:09.465
I'm sure you are.

09:21.144 --> 09:23.812
Well, just look at my car.

09:23.897 --> 09:26.065
And just look what
a mess I'm in, too.

09:26.149 --> 09:29.652
Oh, no, I think
you're beautiful.

09:29.736 --> 09:30.986
And I like your car.

09:31.529 --> 09:32.696
Hmm.

09:33.323 --> 09:36.075
Just the same,
you shouldn't be rushing
across the road like that.

09:36.159 --> 09:37.660
You know, you might
have been killed.

09:38.370 --> 09:40.663
Anyway, why aren't
you in school?

09:41.998 --> 09:43.707
It isn't a holiday, is it?

09:43.792 --> 09:45.000
No, miss.

09:46.086 --> 09:47.419
Do you live around here?

09:47.504 --> 09:49.088
Yes, we live just
down the road.

09:49.172 --> 09:52.132
Come on, get into my car,
I'm taking you home.

09:53.134 --> 09:56.595
Gosh, just wait till
Daddy hears we've been
for a ride in a motorcar!

09:56.680 --> 09:57.763
Yes!

09:59.975 --> 10:01.016
What's your name?

10:01.101 --> 10:02.101
I'm Jemima.

10:02.185 --> 10:03.394
And I'm Jeremy.

10:03.478 --> 10:05.187
What's yours?
Truly.

10:05.272 --> 10:07.314
That's a very
pretty name.

10:07.649 --> 10:09.858
Now, where is your house?

10:10.318 --> 10:11.360
Oh, we don't live
in a house.

10:11.444 --> 10:13.779
We live in the castle
on top of the hill.

10:13.863 --> 10:17.741
A castle? I didn't know
there were any castles
around here.

10:17.826 --> 10:20.202
Well, it isn't
a castle exactly.

10:20.287 --> 10:21.745
That's what
Daddy calls it.

10:21.830 --> 10:25.874
He says King Alfred
used to live there
hundreds of years ago.

10:25.959 --> 10:28.460
And does your daddy know
you aren't in school?

10:28.545 --> 10:30.838
Oh, he won't mind.
He never does.

10:30.922 --> 10:32.965
Anyway,
he's awfully busy.

10:33.049 --> 10:34.133
Is he?

10:34.217 --> 10:37.261
Well, he'll have to
find time to see me,

10:37.345 --> 10:39.680
because I have
a few things to say to him.

10:52.569 --> 10:54.486
JEMlMA: Edison! Edison!

10:54.571 --> 10:56.030
JEREMY: Come here, boy!

10:56.114 --> 10:57.865
Good boy, good boy.

10:57.949 --> 10:59.825
That's Daddy
over there.

10:59.909 --> 11:01.410
JEMlMA: Hello!
JEREMY: Hello!

11:01.870 --> 11:03.954
Hello.
You're just in time.

11:09.210 --> 11:10.836
What on earth
is he up to?

11:10.920 --> 11:12.546
JEMlMA: That's his
latest invention.

11:12.630 --> 11:13.672
Rockets.

11:13.757 --> 11:14.923
Rockets?

11:16.926 --> 11:18.385
Stand back!

11:18.803 --> 11:20.429
Keep clear!

11:22.599 --> 11:25.517
Hooray!
Hooray!

11:31.608 --> 11:32.900
(BARKING)

11:41.117 --> 11:42.368
Does he know
what he's doing?

11:42.452 --> 11:43.744
Of course he does.

11:45.205 --> 11:46.663
Whoa!

12:03.681 --> 12:05.182
(EXCLAIMING)

12:05.266 --> 12:07.226
Well, I don't see
anything funny.

12:07.310 --> 12:09.228
Somebody should do
something about it.

12:13.983 --> 12:16.026
Hold on! Hold on!

12:17.237 --> 12:18.987
Wait! Wait there.

12:29.749 --> 12:30.999
Oh!

12:32.627 --> 12:33.710
Thank you!

12:33.795 --> 12:34.920
I should hope so.

12:35.004 --> 12:36.588
You might have
gone up in flames.

12:36.673 --> 12:39.174
Madam, I took that
into consideration.

12:39.259 --> 12:40.926
This suit is
completely flameproof.

12:41.010 --> 12:42.386
Oh, dear.

12:42.762 --> 12:45.264
You have just
succeeded in ruining
my propulsion unit.

12:45.348 --> 12:46.598
But how was l
to know that you were. . .

12:46.683 --> 12:48.600
Don't be cross
with the lady, Daddy.

12:48.685 --> 12:50.269
JEREMY: She gave us
a ride in her car.

12:50.353 --> 12:51.395
JEMlMA: She was only
trying to help.

12:51.479 --> 12:52.438
How very kind.

12:52.522 --> 12:54.189
Her name's Truly.
That's nice.

12:54.274 --> 12:55.441
Do you realize,
Mr. Potts,

12:55.525 --> 12:57.359
that I nearly knocked down
your two children?

12:57.444 --> 12:59.945
Well, we do seem
to be accident-prone,
don't we?

13:00.029 --> 13:02.364
But it wasn't my fault.
You see, they came
rushing out. . .

13:02.449 --> 13:04.283
Oh, well, it was very,
very nice of you
to apologize.

13:04.367 --> 13:05.617
Apologize?
Tea time, children.

13:05.702 --> 13:06.785
Bye-bye, Truly.

13:06.870 --> 13:07.870
Thanks for the ride.

13:07.954 --> 13:09.163
Just a moment,
you two.

13:09.247 --> 13:11.248
Don't you have
something to
tell your father?

13:11.332 --> 13:15.043
Yes, we have.
Daddy, Mr. Coggins
promised us. . .

13:15.128 --> 13:17.254
But she didn't
mean about that.

13:17.338 --> 13:20.090
Daddy, we didn't go
to school today.

13:21.384 --> 13:22.676
Oh-ho.

13:22.969 --> 13:25.804
Well, it'll give the
other children a chance
to catch up, won't it?

13:25.889 --> 13:27.097
Run along, children.

13:27.182 --> 13:28.765
Goodbye.
Goodbye. Bye, Truly.

13:28.850 --> 13:29.850
Come on, Edison.

13:29.934 --> 13:31.477
But, Mr. Potts. . .
Good day!

13:31.561 --> 13:34.521
But, but. . .
Unstable.
Definitely unstable.

13:35.064 --> 13:36.356
(GRANDPA EXCLAIMS)

13:41.988 --> 13:45.782
Good afternoon, miss.
Sorry I can't stop.
I'm off to India.

13:45.867 --> 13:49.286
Going to have
a cup of tea with
the Maharajah. Cheerio!

14:26.950 --> 14:31.328
Mr. Potts.

14:31.996 --> 14:34.331
I'm sorry to
persist about this,

14:35.124 --> 14:37.167
but perhaps you
simply aren't aware
that your children

14:37.252 --> 14:38.710
were running
about in the road.

14:38.795 --> 14:40.712
And after all, you know,
it's not a playground.
It's very. . .

14:40.797 --> 14:43.006
Would you mind
just pressing
that switch there?

14:43.091 --> 14:44.883
Switch?
Yes, just behind you.

14:44.968 --> 14:46.301
On the right.
The right.

14:46.386 --> 14:47.636
The right?

14:49.222 --> 14:50.264
Thank you.

14:50.348 --> 14:52.724
You really ought
to try and exercise
more control over them.

14:52.809 --> 14:55.394
Yes, I suppose I could
chain them up, couldn't l?

14:55.478 --> 14:56.979
On a nice long chain,
of course,

14:57.063 --> 14:58.397
so they get
plenty of exercise.

14:58.481 --> 15:00.983
Mr. Potts,
don't your children
go to school?

15:01.067 --> 15:02.776
Oh, I have it now.
You're the
truant officer.

15:02.860 --> 15:04.570
No, I'm not
the truant officer.

15:04.654 --> 15:07.155
Well, didn't you
ever play truant?
I mean, just once?

15:07.240 --> 15:09.157
No, I most
certainly did not.

15:09.867 --> 15:11.618
I bet you didn't.

15:12.537 --> 15:17.207
Would it be too much
to ask what this is,
this, um, thing?

15:17.292 --> 15:20.419
A little invention of mine,
cleans carpets by suction.

15:20.503 --> 15:22.254
All that to clean carpets?

15:22.338 --> 15:24.881
Away with sweeping,
and away with brushing,

15:24.966 --> 15:26.967
and away with
dirty carpets.

15:28.845 --> 15:30.345
(LAUGHING)

15:32.015 --> 15:35.559
Is that all you do,
Mr. Potts? Invent things?

15:35.643 --> 15:36.768
Is that all I do?

15:36.853 --> 15:38.103
And what's this gadget?

15:38.187 --> 15:39.563
Well, that's not
quite right yet,

15:39.647 --> 15:43.525
but eventually,
I hope to transmit
moving pictures by wireless.

15:44.402 --> 15:46.403
Oh, really?
Yes, really.
That's my. . .

15:46.487 --> 15:47.946
And this?

15:48.031 --> 15:50.824
This, madam,
is a sweet-making machine.

15:55.163 --> 15:56.455
And is this one
of the sweets?

15:56.539 --> 15:57.789
Yes, it is.

15:57.874 --> 16:00.292
And is it supposed to have
all those holes in it?

16:00.376 --> 16:03.086
No. Actually, I think
that the problem is. . .

16:03.171 --> 16:05.547
The boiling point of
your sugar is too high.

16:05.632 --> 16:07.049
Oh, we're an expert on
sweet-making, are we?

16:07.133 --> 16:08.216
Well,
as a matter of fact. . .

16:08.301 --> 16:10.302
And an expert
on child welfare.

16:10.386 --> 16:12.054
I was only trying to
help your children.

16:12.138 --> 16:14.389
Well, maybe my children
like running wild
in the street.

16:14.474 --> 16:16.308
Did that ever occur to you?
I do not see any cause to. . .

16:16.392 --> 16:18.268
And in any case,
how my children behave

16:18.353 --> 16:19.811
is frankly
no concern of yours.

16:19.896 --> 16:20.937
I was merely trying. . .

16:21.022 --> 16:22.898
So, if you'll be so good
as to take yourself off

16:22.982 --> 16:24.524
in that fancy
automobile of yours

16:24.609 --> 16:26.026
and go do good
somewhere else.

16:26.110 --> 16:27.486
Well, I've never been. . .

16:27.570 --> 16:30.322
Spoken to that way before?
Well, maybe it's about time.

16:30.406 --> 16:32.824
(HUFFS)
Good afternoon, madam.

16:33.201 --> 16:34.743
Mind the cable!

16:37.413 --> 16:39.456
Vicious, interfering. . .

16:41.793 --> 16:43.126
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

16:48.966 --> 16:50.717
If women are
going to drive
motorcars around,

16:50.802 --> 16:52.886
they should learn to
operate one correctly.

16:52.970 --> 16:56.807
Well, I suppose
it wouldn't occur to you
to offer to help me.

17:01.187 --> 17:03.313
Get in the car. Please.

17:10.238 --> 17:12.989
Well, for
a mechanically-minded man,
Mr. Potts. . .

17:13.074 --> 17:14.574
Try switching it on.

17:14.659 --> 17:15.867
Oh.

17:18.413 --> 17:19.579
Hmm!

17:21.833 --> 17:23.250
(ENGINE STARTS)

17:29.132 --> 17:30.424
(GRINDING)

17:31.134 --> 17:32.342
Open the throttle!

17:33.469 --> 17:35.137
And keep it open!

17:37.306 --> 17:38.432
Women!

17:43.563 --> 17:46.982
Confounded woman!
Who does she think she is?

17:47.066 --> 17:50.527
Coming in here
and telling me how
to raise my children.

17:51.320 --> 17:53.238
Do I need somebody
to tell me how
to raise my children?

17:53.489 --> 17:54.740
Do l? Hmm?

17:55.116 --> 17:58.076
No, of course not.
Of course not!

17:59.412 --> 18:00.996
Where's my cardigan?

18:01.205 --> 18:02.372
Under your jacket.

18:02.457 --> 18:03.915
Under. . . Yes.

18:04.834 --> 18:06.835
Self-righteous busybody.

18:07.378 --> 18:08.795
(LAUGHS)

18:08.880 --> 18:09.921
She won't be
bothering us again.

18:10.381 --> 18:11.673
But I liked her.

18:11.841 --> 18:14.885
So did l.
She was very pretty.

18:14.969 --> 18:16.636
She certainly was.

18:18.514 --> 18:22.476
Do you think your
father's a crackpot?

18:22.560 --> 18:24.603
Your cardigan's
inside out.

18:24.687 --> 18:25.979
Oh.

18:26.481 --> 18:27.773
Do you think
I'm a lunatic,

18:27.857 --> 18:29.983
wasting my time on a lot
of silly inventions?

18:30.067 --> 18:32.194
But they aren't silly.
They're wonderful.

18:32.653 --> 18:34.070
Nobody else
could think of them.

18:34.489 --> 18:38.325
That's right. That is right.
Nobody else could
think of them.

18:38.701 --> 18:43.121
Yes. After all,
what makes the battle
worth the fighting?

18:43.956 --> 18:46.041
What makes the mountain
worth the climb?

18:46.125 --> 18:48.335
What makes the questions
worth the asking?

18:49.212 --> 18:50.712
The reason worth
the rhyme?

18:53.049 --> 18:56.468
(SINGING) To me,
the answer's clear

18:57.053 --> 19:00.514
It's having someone near

19:00.890 --> 19:02.974
Someone dear

19:05.645 --> 19:09.564
Someone to care for
To be there for

19:09.941 --> 19:13.235
I have you two

19:13.402 --> 19:16.905
Someone to do for
Muddle through for

19:17.573 --> 19:20.575
I have you two

19:20.660 --> 19:24.454
Someone to share
joy or despair with

19:24.914 --> 19:27.707
Whichever betides you

19:28.125 --> 19:30.961
Life becomes a chore

19:31.712 --> 19:35.257
Unless you're living for

19:35.508 --> 19:39.386
Someone to tend to,
be a friend to

19:39.762 --> 19:42.597
I have you two

19:42.932 --> 19:47.060
Someone to strive for
Do or die for

19:47.353 --> 19:50.188
I have you two

19:51.023 --> 19:57.320
Could be we three
get along so famously

19:57.530 --> 20:01.199
'Cause you two have me

20:01.617 --> 20:04.619
And I have you two, too

20:15.381 --> 20:16.798
(CHEERING)

20:18.551 --> 20:19.885
(SHATTERING)

20:33.733 --> 20:35.066
(BELL DINGS)

20:35.151 --> 20:36.401
(TOOTING)

21:09.810 --> 21:11.186
(SNEEZES)

21:11.270 --> 21:14.940
BOTH: Someone to care for
To be there for

21:15.524 --> 21:18.526
I have you two

21:18.819 --> 21:22.822
Someone to do for
Muddle through for

21:22.907 --> 21:26.201
I have you two

21:26.452 --> 21:30.413
Someone to smile
once in a while with

21:30.873 --> 21:33.667
Whenever you're lonesome

21:34.210 --> 21:37.045
I've a happy lot

21:37.546 --> 21:40.715
Considering what I've got

21:41.050 --> 21:43.551
But I couldn't do more

21:43.928 --> 21:47.305
Than you do for
your poor father

21:47.390 --> 21:48.890
Daddy!
Daddy!

21:49.100 --> 21:50.725
Things go asunder

21:51.310 --> 21:55.146
And I wonder why you bother

21:57.066 --> 22:00.110
ALL: Could be we three

22:00.736 --> 22:04.072
Get along so famously 'cause

22:04.573 --> 22:07.575
BOTH: We two have you

22:07.660 --> 22:11.579
And I have you two

22:14.417 --> 22:15.709
Too

22:19.088 --> 22:20.171
(EXCLAIMS)

22:20.256 --> 22:21.464
Jeremy.

22:22.049 --> 22:23.216
Oh, good.

22:25.094 --> 22:26.219
Do I smell food?

22:27.471 --> 22:28.596
Bring the bread,
will you, Grandpa.

22:28.681 --> 22:29.723
Yes, sir! Sir! Sir!

22:29.807 --> 22:31.016
And pepper
and salt, please.

22:31.100 --> 22:32.600
Right away, sir!

22:33.602 --> 22:34.686
Oh!

22:34.770 --> 22:36.813
Sausage and egg,
my favorite!

22:36.897 --> 22:38.398
How was India?
India?

22:38.482 --> 22:41.192
I'll tell you something.
I got up this morning,

22:41.277 --> 22:43.695
and I shot an elephant
in my pajamas.
How he ever. . .

22:43.779 --> 22:46.781
ALL: Got into my pajamas,
I shall never know.

22:46.866 --> 22:47.949
You've heard it before.

22:48.034 --> 22:49.242
(ALL LAUGHING)

22:57.793 --> 22:59.419
Now, I wonder how that
could have happened.

22:59.628 --> 23:01.921
Daddy, could we
ask you something?

23:02.006 --> 23:03.048
It's about Mr. Coggins.

23:03.132 --> 23:04.174
Mr. Coggins.

23:04.258 --> 23:06.676
You see, the junkman
wanted to take it away.

23:06.761 --> 23:08.887
But Mr. Coggins says
if we asked you first. . .

23:08.971 --> 23:10.221
Asked me what first?

23:10.306 --> 23:12.015
He's a horrid,
mean, old man.

23:12.099 --> 23:13.141
Mr. Coggins?

23:13.225 --> 23:14.350
No, the junkman.

23:14.435 --> 23:15.477
He's going to
take it away

23:15.561 --> 23:17.687
and put it in a furnace.
And burn it all up.
It's terrible.

23:17.772 --> 23:18.980
What are you
going on about?

23:19.065 --> 23:20.398
BOTH: Our car!

23:20.483 --> 23:21.566
Yes, well, what about it?

23:21.650 --> 23:24.444
Mr. Coggins is selling it
to the junkman.

23:24.528 --> 23:27.489
And the junkman's
going to put it
in the fiery furnace.

23:27.573 --> 23:30.533
And squidge it all up
till there's nothing left.

23:30.618 --> 23:33.161
Oh, well, that's terrible.
That is terrible.

23:33.329 --> 23:35.288
We can't let
that happen, Grandpa.

23:36.791 --> 23:38.166
No, definitely not.

23:38.667 --> 23:40.001
We knew you
wouldn't let them, Daddy.

23:40.086 --> 23:42.545
So we made Mr.
Coggins promise
we could have it

23:42.630 --> 23:44.839
if you gave him
30 shillings.

23:47.468 --> 23:48.593
Uh, 30 shillings.

23:48.677 --> 23:52.180
JEREMY: You can give
Mr. Coggins the money
in the morning, Daddy.

23:52.264 --> 23:56.267
Yes, well, I suppose we can
work something out somehow.

23:56.352 --> 23:57.769
Good!
Hooray!

23:58.354 --> 23:59.813
Are you all finished?

23:59.897 --> 24:01.189
Yes, Daddy.
Yes, thank you.

24:01.273 --> 24:03.900
Well, I think, maybe,
you should go run up to bed.

24:04.026 --> 24:05.944
Good night, Grandpa.
Good night, my boy.
Sleep tight.

24:06.070 --> 24:07.946
Good night, Grandpa.
Good night, my darling.
God bless you.

24:08.030 --> 24:09.614
Good night, Daddy.
Good night.

24:09.698 --> 24:11.366
Good night, Daddy.

24:15.830 --> 24:19.582
Yes, well,
you've done it now,
haven't you?

24:21.794 --> 24:23.795
You think Coggins
might do a deal?
So much a week?

24:23.879 --> 24:26.589
Coggins? What,
him down the road? Sure.

24:26.966 --> 24:30.510
He's so mean
he wouldn't light your pipe
if his house was on fire.

24:30.594 --> 24:32.554
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

24:32.638 --> 24:35.640
Did you hear that?
You know what that means,
don't you?

24:35.724 --> 24:38.476
I'll be up all night,
rain pouring through
my bedroom roof.

24:38.561 --> 24:42.021
Grandpa, why don't you
sleep in the workshop?
It's nice and. . .

24:42.106 --> 24:43.731
The workshop?

24:43.816 --> 24:45.984
You promised, faithfully,
to fix my bedroom roof.

24:46.068 --> 24:47.318
I will, Grandpa.
It's just. . .

24:47.403 --> 24:49.946
Caractacus, please.
My boy, listen.

24:51.240 --> 24:54.868
It's time you woke up.
When I was your age,
I did a day's work. . .

24:54.952 --> 24:57.162
For a day's pay,
polishing
the Colonel's boots.

24:57.246 --> 24:58.663
I was the smartest batman
in the British Army.

24:58.747 --> 24:59.831
So you've been
telling me.

24:59.915 --> 25:01.040
When my Brigadier
went into action,

25:01.125 --> 25:04.085
the fuzzy-wuzzies
were so blinded
by the shine on his boots,

25:04.170 --> 25:05.879
they couldn't see to fight.

25:05.963 --> 25:08.047
(RUMBLING CONTINUES)
(EXCLAIMS)

25:13.971 --> 25:16.806
Catch me death of cold.
He doesn't care.

25:17.641 --> 25:20.476
Nobody cares.
Me own son!

25:44.460 --> 25:47.712
She was right.
Who wants sweets
with holes in them?

25:54.678 --> 25:55.929
(WHISTLING)

25:57.723 --> 25:59.557
Oh, Edison,
stop that whistling.

25:59.642 --> 26:00.975
(WHISTLING CONTINUES)

26:06.398 --> 26:08.608
Edison, hey,
do that again.

26:09.568 --> 26:11.152
(WHISTLING)

26:17.159 --> 26:20.411
Edison, you're a genius.

26:24.124 --> 26:25.291
(BARKING)

26:34.343 --> 26:36.219
The employment office
is in the rear.

26:36.303 --> 26:37.679
Thank you. Oh.

26:39.556 --> 26:42.600
You see, I've invented
these sweets.

26:42.685 --> 26:44.143
Really?

26:44.228 --> 26:45.311
Name?

26:45.437 --> 26:46.479
Uh. . .

26:46.855 --> 26:49.649
Whistling Sweets.
Mr. Whistling Sweets.

26:50.150 --> 26:52.277
(LAUGHING)
Not Mr. Whistling Sweets.

26:53.028 --> 26:55.113
No, I'm Potts.

26:55.197 --> 26:56.364
Hmm.

26:57.366 --> 26:59.200
May I see
the managing director?

26:59.285 --> 27:01.786
Lord Scrumptious sees no one
without an appointment.

27:01.870 --> 27:02.996
CARACTACUS: Well, how do l
get an appointment?

27:03.080 --> 27:04.414
Why, hello, children.

27:04.498 --> 27:06.165
JEMlMA: Jeremy, it's Truly.

27:06.250 --> 27:07.292
Hello, Truly.

27:07.376 --> 27:09.752
Good morning,
Miss Scrumptious.
How nice to see you.

27:09.837 --> 27:12.797
Good morning, Phillips.
Please tell my father
that I'm here.

27:12.881 --> 27:15.216
But of course,
Miss Scrumptious.

27:15.801 --> 27:17.760
Are you here
on business, Mr. Potts?

27:17.845 --> 27:19.429
Yes, Miss. . .

27:20.723 --> 27:24.350
Father?
Truly Scrumptious.

27:24.643 --> 27:25.643
You're his. . .

27:25.728 --> 27:26.978
His daughter.
Mmm-hmm.

27:28.397 --> 27:29.480
Come on, children,
let's go.

27:29.565 --> 27:31.691
But, Daddy,
you haven't shown
anybody your invention.

27:31.775 --> 27:33.568
Somehow, I don't think
that'll do much good.

27:33.652 --> 27:35.320
Just a moment,
Mr. Potts.

27:35.404 --> 27:36.738
Exactly what was it you. . .

27:36.822 --> 27:38.281
You've seen them.

27:38.365 --> 27:40.199
Oh, those.
But they whistle.

27:40.284 --> 27:41.576
Whistle?

27:41.827 --> 27:43.202
Those holes.

27:43.287 --> 27:45.455
You just blow through them.

27:47.166 --> 27:48.416
(WHISTLES)

27:50.085 --> 27:51.836
They're very ingenious.

27:51.920 --> 27:53.588
Kind of a novelty.

27:53.797 --> 27:55.173
(SHUSHING)

27:55.257 --> 27:57.050
Please go in,
Miss Scrumptious.

27:57.176 --> 27:58.926
You can come back
in three weeks' time.

27:59.011 --> 28:00.928
Show Mr. Potts in,
Phillips.

28:01.013 --> 28:02.180
Now?
Now.

28:02.264 --> 28:04.098
But his Lordship said. . .
Now.

28:04.183 --> 28:06.601
Very well.
Please follow me.

28:07.936 --> 28:09.395
Maybe I should come
back in three weeks.

28:09.480 --> 28:10.855
Oh, Daddy!

28:10.939 --> 28:12.482
Go on, Daddy.

28:13.942 --> 28:15.276
All right.

28:17.529 --> 28:19.655
And don't let him
bully you.

28:20.032 --> 28:21.199
Yes.

28:23.285 --> 28:24.952
Mr. Potts, milord.

28:25.245 --> 28:26.788
Potts? Who's he?

28:26.872 --> 28:27.914
Where's me daughter?

28:27.998 --> 28:29.957
She insisted on
Mr. Potts seeing you.

28:30.376 --> 28:33.044
All right,
don't just stand there.
What's it all about?

28:33.545 --> 28:34.629
Sweets, sir.

28:34.713 --> 28:37.799
I hardly thought it
was nuts and bolts.
Let's have a look.

28:37.883 --> 28:39.008
Yes.

28:40.135 --> 28:42.136
Hurry up, man!
Yes, sir.

28:43.263 --> 28:44.889
If I may be allowed
to explain, sir.

28:44.973 --> 28:46.432
You have exactly
20 seconds.

28:46.517 --> 28:47.683
Yes.

28:47.768 --> 28:49.602
Well, the fundamental
novelty of these
particular sweets

28:49.686 --> 28:51.562
is their musical quality.

28:51.688 --> 28:54.357
Not only are they
remarkably tasty,

28:54.441 --> 28:57.652
but due to
the unique positioning
of these little holes,

28:57.736 --> 29:00.071
they are capable,
when blown through,

29:00.155 --> 29:02.490
of rendering
a tuneful whistle.

29:03.158 --> 29:05.535
Place your fingers
over the holes
and blow thus.

29:05.869 --> 29:07.829
(STEAM WHISTLE BLOWING LOUDLY)

29:10.165 --> 29:11.582
Tasting time, milord.

29:11.834 --> 29:15.461
Too late. Had your chance.
Muffed it. Good morning.

29:19.466 --> 29:20.842
(WHISPERING)
Go on. Follow him.

29:22.094 --> 29:23.136
Milord?

29:29.268 --> 29:31.018
(BLOWING WHISTLE)

29:32.813 --> 29:33.938
CARACTACUS: Sir?

29:34.022 --> 29:35.231
Excuse me.

29:35.315 --> 29:37.066
Sir, if I may be
allowed to demonstrate.

29:37.151 --> 29:39.402
You see, by blowing air
through this hole
in the center of the sweet

29:39.486 --> 29:40.611
you get a
wonderful-sounding. . .

29:40.696 --> 29:42.238
Raspberry?
No, no.

29:42.322 --> 29:43.531
It's more like
a toot, really.

29:43.615 --> 29:45.199
Not enough fruit,
too much sugar.
Yes, milord.

29:45.284 --> 29:46.409
Prepare the peppermint.

29:46.493 --> 29:47.785
Beautiful. Would you
care to try it, sir?

29:47.870 --> 29:49.203
Under no circumstances.

29:49.288 --> 29:50.496
Prepare the lemon!

29:50.581 --> 29:52.623
He's not doing
very well, is he?

29:52.708 --> 29:55.793
You know, another
remarkable feature about
these little sweets

29:55.878 --> 29:57.753
is that by
sucking on them. . .
Throw it away!

29:57.838 --> 29:59.380
Will you get rid of
this idiot for me?

29:59.465 --> 30:01.090
Milord. You.
. . .in perfect pitch.

30:01.175 --> 30:03.301
They also come in
strawberry, raspberry. . .

30:03.385 --> 30:05.553
Are you still here?
. . .lemon and. . .

30:05.679 --> 30:07.221
And pineapple.

30:08.557 --> 30:09.557
(MOUTHING) Go on.

30:14.730 --> 30:15.897
(CLEARS THROAT)

30:15.981 --> 30:18.900
Don't waste your pucker
on some all-day sucker.

30:19.359 --> 30:22.278
And don't try
a toffee or cream.

30:23.405 --> 30:25.865
If you seek perfection
in sugar confection,

30:25.949 --> 30:28.868
well, there's something
new on the scene.

30:28.952 --> 30:32.288
A mouthful of cheer,
a sweet without peer.

30:32.748 --> 30:36.459
(SINGING)
A musical morsel supreme

30:38.879 --> 30:41.964
Toot sweets, toot sweets

30:42.049 --> 30:43.841
The candies you whistle

30:43.926 --> 30:45.259
The whistles you eat

30:45.886 --> 30:48.930
Toot sweets, toot sweets

30:49.014 --> 30:51.933
The eatable,
tweetable treats

30:53.018 --> 30:55.895
Toot sweets, toot sweets

30:55.979 --> 30:59.357
The toot of a flute
with the flavor of fruit

30:59.816 --> 31:02.902
Toot sweets, toot sweets

31:02.986 --> 31:05.613
No longer need candy be mute

31:06.907 --> 31:09.867
Don't waste your pucker
on some all-day sucker

31:09.952 --> 31:12.870
And don't try
a toffee or cream

31:13.455 --> 31:16.666
If you seek perfection
in sugar confection

31:16.750 --> 31:19.544
Well, there's something
new on the scene

31:20.254 --> 31:22.046
That mouthful of cheer

31:22.130 --> 31:23.923
That sweet without peer

31:24.007 --> 31:28.219
That musical morsel supreme
That musical morsel supreme

31:30.806 --> 31:33.891
BOTH: Toot sweets,
toot sweets

31:33.976 --> 31:37.853
A bonbon to blow on
at last has been found

31:37.938 --> 31:40.898
Toot sweets, toot sweets

31:40.983 --> 31:44.318
With tweetable,
eatable sound

31:44.903 --> 31:46.779
No! Take it away!

31:51.577 --> 31:54.453
Father, please.

31:59.459 --> 32:00.668
(TOOTS)

32:00.752 --> 32:01.794
(CHUCKLES)

32:02.713 --> 32:04.005
(LAUGHING)

32:10.095 --> 32:11.470
He likes it!

32:11.555 --> 32:12.888
(ALL CHEERING)

32:14.975 --> 32:16.726
(SINGING) Their value
is intrinsic

32:16.810 --> 32:18.477
Surpass any mint stick

32:18.562 --> 32:21.439
BOTH: Or marshmallow
mouthful you munch

32:22.357 --> 32:23.858
Though licorice is chewy

32:23.942 --> 32:25.818
And gumdrops are gooey

32:25.902 --> 32:28.446
And chocolate is
charming to crunch

32:29.698 --> 32:31.365
That savory fife

32:31.575 --> 32:33.492
That sweet of your life

32:33.577 --> 32:37.830
It's clearly
the best of the bunch

32:38.582 --> 32:57.391
Toot sweets, toot sweets

33:43.563 --> 33:45.439
That savory fife

33:47.317 --> 33:49.568
That sweet of your life

33:51.029 --> 33:56.367
Is clearly
the best of the bunch

34:00.122 --> 34:05.209
Toot sweets, toot sweets

34:05.293 --> 34:09.672
A bonbon to blow on
at last has been found

34:09.922 --> 34:13.717
Toot sweets, toot sweets

34:13.802 --> 34:16.053
The treat
that's so tweetable

34:16.138 --> 34:17.972
Lusciously eatable

34:18.056 --> 34:21.058
With that unbeatable

34:30.025 --> 34:31.860
(ALL TOOTING)

34:32.696 --> 34:33.696
(BARKS)

34:39.745 --> 34:41.245
(ALL BARKING)

34:46.168 --> 34:47.333
(EXCLAIMING)

34:53.341 --> 34:54.507
(DOGS BARKING)

34:55.761 --> 34:56.761
(WHISTLES HIGH NOTE)

34:56.844 --> 34:59.263
Sound

35:00.849 --> 35:04.018
Get out of here!
Go away!

35:04.102 --> 35:05.478
(ALL CLAMORING)

35:07.481 --> 35:09.440
What's going on?

35:09.524 --> 35:11.358
Get those dogs out of here!

35:21.328 --> 35:22.578
Edison, no!

35:22.662 --> 35:23.871
Edison! Edison!

35:24.372 --> 35:25.831
Children!
JEMlMA: Edison!

35:28.210 --> 35:29.794
Edison!

35:30.587 --> 35:33.547
It's entirely your fault.
I'll send for the police.

35:34.674 --> 35:35.800
(EXCLAIMS)

36:09.793 --> 36:11.252
Daddy.

36:12.379 --> 36:14.713
Now, why aren't
you two asleep?

36:15.131 --> 36:17.049
Don't be sad,
Daddy.

36:17.384 --> 36:18.801
It wasn't your fault.

36:18.885 --> 36:21.178
It was all those
mean, old dogs.

36:24.015 --> 36:25.432
Children,

36:26.768 --> 36:28.185
about the car. . .

36:28.895 --> 36:30.187
You see,

36:31.356 --> 36:34.024
30 shillings is
pretty hard to come by.

36:35.151 --> 36:38.946
And when I do get any money,
I need it for my inventions.

36:41.449 --> 36:43.325
Well, there isn't
any left.

36:43.410 --> 36:45.369
Jeremy and l
have been thinking.

36:45.453 --> 36:47.121
It's our treasure chest.

36:47.205 --> 36:49.456
These things are
enormously valuable.

36:49.958 --> 36:52.042
Look, an ivory tusk.

36:52.127 --> 36:54.211
JEREMY: That must be
worth a fortune.

36:54.296 --> 36:55.963
JEMlMA: And diamonds.

36:56.423 --> 36:58.382
And a golden crown.

36:58.466 --> 37:00.092
It's probably
King Alfred's.

37:00.176 --> 37:02.553
Of course, it needs
cleaning up a little.

37:02.637 --> 37:04.513
Take them, Daddy.
You can sell them.

37:05.974 --> 37:09.393
And never mind about the car.
You can spend it all
on your inventions.

37:12.439 --> 37:14.148
Thank you, children.

37:16.067 --> 37:18.402
All these wonderful things,

37:19.154 --> 37:20.988
they're very precious.

37:22.073 --> 37:24.992
But I'm afraid other people
wouldn't appreciate them.

37:25.327 --> 37:26.660
Why not, Daddy?

37:27.996 --> 37:31.206
Because other people
don't see things
the way you do.

37:31.291 --> 37:33.542
Come on, now.
Let's go to bed.

37:35.462 --> 37:37.212
And don't you worry.

37:38.089 --> 37:39.423
Things are going to
come right somehow.

37:42.761 --> 37:44.845
(GENTLE MUSIC TINKLING)

37:59.152 --> 38:01.362
(SINGING) A gentle breeze

38:01.905 --> 38:04.448
from Hushabye Mountain

38:05.367 --> 38:07.701
Softly blows

38:08.203 --> 38:11.372
o'er Lullaby Bay

38:13.083 --> 38:15.376
It fills the sails

38:16.378 --> 38:19.588
of boats that are waiting

38:20.048 --> 38:26.220
Waiting to sail
your worries away

38:34.229 --> 38:36.563
It isn't far

38:37.565 --> 38:40.275
to Hushabye Mountain

38:41.611 --> 38:47.533
And your boat
waits down by the quay

38:49.119 --> 38:51.578
The winds of night

38:52.247 --> 38:55.416
so softly are sighing

38:56.501 --> 39:02.923
Soon they will fly
your troubles to sea

39:05.510 --> 39:12.307
So close your eyes
on Hushabye Mountain

39:14.269 --> 39:20.274
Wave goodbye to
cares of the day

39:21.776 --> 39:24.319
And watch your boat

39:25.447 --> 39:28.157
from Hushabye Mountain

39:29.826 --> 39:33.704
Sail far away

39:33.955 --> 39:36.957
from Lullaby Bay

40:11.326 --> 40:13.660
(CIRCUS MARCH
PLAYlNG DlSTANTLY)

40:43.108 --> 40:46.318
All the lovely colors.
Two for the price of one.

40:46.444 --> 40:48.195
Get your
balloons here!
(TOOTING HORN)

41:07.382 --> 41:09.550
MAN: Hurry, hurry,
hurry along now.

41:10.635 --> 41:12.803
Don't miss these
lovely toffee apples!

41:12.887 --> 41:15.889
Hurry along now!
Get your toffee
apples at 8p each.

41:15.974 --> 41:19.268
Thank you very much,
young man.
Any more for any more?

41:20.228 --> 41:23.063
Which one of you
lovely ladies
and gentlemen

41:23.148 --> 41:25.482
would like a splendid,
automatic haircut?

41:25.567 --> 41:27.651
I've stood in this
marketplace for 25 years.

41:27.735 --> 41:29.862
I do not profess to
make dead men talk!

41:29.946 --> 41:33.365
(LOUDLY) Hey, now,
here you go then. Who's for
an automatic haircut?

41:33.449 --> 41:35.117
Only three pence a time.

41:35.201 --> 41:37.828
You may have long hair,
you may have short hair, sir,

41:37.912 --> 41:40.164
you may have straight hair,
it makes no difference

41:40.248 --> 41:42.124
to the Potts
automatic and hygienic,

41:42.208 --> 41:43.500
electronic
hair-cutting machine!

41:44.544 --> 41:45.544
(DINGING)

41:48.131 --> 41:49.798
(CLAMORING)

41:50.133 --> 41:52.676
Come on.
You could do
with a haircut.

41:52.760 --> 41:54.803
Cut me hair?
That's where
me strength is.

41:54.888 --> 41:57.306
Excuse me, sir,
you look like a man who
could do with a haircut.

41:57.390 --> 41:59.516
Bah!
Yeah, go on! Go on.

41:59.601 --> 42:01.602
Come on, sit down.
Hold that, then.

42:01.686 --> 42:03.103
My word,
you have a lot of hair.

42:03.188 --> 42:04.521
Would you like
an estimate, sir?

42:04.606 --> 42:07.316
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)
Very funny.
Go on, get on with it.

42:07.400 --> 42:11.028
You just sit tight, sir,
while I lower this
hair-cutting machine.

42:11.112 --> 42:14.114
There we are.
You just relax, we'll have
you finished in a bit.

42:14.199 --> 42:16.158
I feel like a real
right nana sitting here.

42:16.242 --> 42:19.620
No, you look lovely, Cyril.
It's going to be smashing.

42:20.955 --> 42:22.581
You keep your eyes
on that geezer.

42:22.665 --> 42:24.124
Yeah, all right, then.

42:25.960 --> 42:27.002
What's going on?

42:27.086 --> 42:28.170
It's all right,
Cyril, it's all right.

42:28.463 --> 42:31.632
Nothing to worry about, sir,
a little friction to start.

42:33.635 --> 42:35.260
It tickles!

42:35.345 --> 42:37.054
Oh, you always
say that, Cyril.

42:37.180 --> 42:38.472
(ALL LAUGHING)

42:49.484 --> 42:50.901
Oh! Oh! Oh!

42:50.985 --> 42:54.071
Cyril, you're smoking!

42:54.405 --> 42:55.447
I'm on fire!

42:55.907 --> 42:57.032
(SCREAMS)

42:57.116 --> 42:58.659
Stop it!
Oh!

42:59.869 --> 43:01.161
Excuse me!

43:01.246 --> 43:02.454
Me head's on fire!

43:02.538 --> 43:04.289
It's all right, sir.

43:04.374 --> 43:05.540
(GASPS)

43:05.625 --> 43:06.917
(ALL LAUGHING)

43:07.418 --> 43:10.295
